# Audit records

For any durable, auditable body an LLM agent authors — git commit, PR description,
Jira comment, incident note, change record — make authorship and rationale explicit.

## Attribution & rationale

- State agent authorship via an `Authored By` field naming the tool/agent used.
- Include a concise summary explaining each material change and WHY.
- If materially changing a Jira ticket's saved fields (title, description, acceptance
  criteria, scope, status), add a Jira comment recording each change + rationale.

## Commit co-authorship (agent GitHub identity)

The human is commit author and committer; the agent machine user is co-author.
Append this exact trailer to every agent-authored commit:

```text
Co-Authored-By: {{ .my.github_agent.username }} <{{ .my.github_agent.email }}>
```
{{- if hasPrefix "dot_claude/" $.chezmoi.sourceFile }}

Claude Code appends this trailer automatically via the `attribution.commit`
setting — do **not** add it manually here.
{{- end }}

## Compact metadata (keep it greppable)

Include: `Co-Authored-By`, `Model`, `Model-Provider`, `Session-ID`, `Username`, `Hostname`.
Record each value's source inline — e.g. `Model: claude-opus-4-8 (source: session)`.
Terse source labels: `session` for live runtime values; the config filename for applied
config (e.g. `~/.codex/config.toml`).

## Resolution order (per attribute)

1. Current live session / runtime context (incl. status/UI metadata).
2. Active applied config — NOT repo templates or dotfile source.

Never assume or guess a metadata value — if it cannot be dynamically read from a source
of truth, default to `unknown (source: unavailable)`. Copy values exactly as shown — never
infer from API base URLs, proxies, or assumed vendors.
